\begin_layout Standard
In a mixture which finds itself in a vapor-liquid equilibria state (VLE),
 the component fugacities are the same in all phases, that is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smith1996"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f_{i}^{L}=f_{i}^{V}\label{eq:elv1}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fugacity of a component in a mixture depends on temperature, pressure
 and composition.
 in order to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{V}$
\end_inset

 with temperature, pressure and molar fraction, we define the fugacity coefficie
nt,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{i}=\frac{f_{i}^{V}}{y_{i}P},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
which can be calculated from PVT data, commonly obtained from an equation
 of state.
 For a mixture of ideal gases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fugacity of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 component in the liquid phase is related to the composition of that phase
 by the activity coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

, which by itself is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and standard-state fugacity 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{i}=\frac{f_{i}^{L}}{x_{i}f_{i}^{0}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard state fugacity 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the fugacity of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th component in the system temperature, i.e.
 mixture, and in an arbitrary pressure and composition.
 in DWSIM, the standard-state fugacity of each component is considered to
 be equal to pure liquid 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at the system temperature and pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If an Equation of State is used to calculate equilibria, fugacity of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th component in the liquid phase is calculated by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{i}=\frac{f_{i}^{L}}{x_{i}P},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
with the fugacity coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 calculated by the EOS, just like it is for the same component in the vapor
 phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fugacity coefficient of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th component either in the liquid or in the vapor phase is obtained from
 the same Equation of State through the following expressions
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
RT\ln\phi_{i}^{L} & = & \intop_{V^{L}}^{\infty}\left[\left(\frac{\partial P}{\partial n_{i}}\right)_{T,V,n_{j}}-\frac{RT}{V}\right]dV-RT\ln Z^{L},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

