\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Peng-Robinson with Volume Translation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Volume translation solves the main problem with two-constant EOS's, poor
 liquid volumetric predictions.
 A simple correction term is applied to the EOS-calculated molar volume,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v=v^{EOS}-c,\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=$
\end_inset

corrected molar volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{EOS}=$
\end_inset

EOS-calculated volume, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=$
\end_inset

component-specific constant.
 The shift in volume is actually equivalent to adding a third constant to
 the EOS but is special because equilibrium conditions are unaltered.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also shown that multicomponent VLE is unaltered by introducing the
 volume-shift term 
\emph on
c 
\emph default
as a mole-fraction average,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{L}=v_{L}^{EOS}-\sum x_{i}c_{i}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Volume translation can be applied to any two-constant cubic equation, thereby
 eliminating the volumetric defficiency suffered by all two-constant equations
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Whitson2000"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Peng-Robinson-Stryjek-Vera
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
PRSV1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A modification to the attraction term in the Peng-Robinson equation of state
 published by Stryjek and Vera in 1986 (PRSV) significantly improved the
 model's accuracy by introducing an adjustable pure component parameter
 and by modifying the polynomial fit of the acentric factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The modification is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\kappa=\kappa_{0}+\kappa_{1}\left(1+T_{r}^{0.5}\right)\left(0.7-T_{r}\right)\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\kappa_{0}=0.378893+1.4897153\,\omega-0.17131848\,\omega^{2}+0.0196554\,\omega^{3}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an adjustable pure component parameter.
 Stryjek and Vera published pure component parameters for many compounds
 of industrial interest in their original journal article.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
PRSV2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subsequent modification published in 1986 (PRSV2) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PRSV2-1986"

\end_inset

 further improved the model's accuracy by introducing two additional pure
 component parameters to the previous attraction term modification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The modification is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\kappa=\kappa_{0}+\left[\kappa_{1}+\kappa_{2}\left(\kappa_{3}-T_{r}\right)\left(1-T_{r}^{0}.5\right)\right]\left(1+T_{r}^{0.5}\right)\left(0.7-T_{r}\right)\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\kappa_{0}=0.378893+1.4897153\,\omega-0.17131848\,\omega^{2}+0.0196554\,\omega^{3}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{3}$
\end_inset

 are adjustable pure component parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PRSV2 is particularly advantageous for VLE calculations.
 While PRSV1 does offer an advantage over the Peng-Robinson model for describing
 thermodynamic behavior, it is still not accurate enough, in general, for
 phase equilibrium calculations.
 The highly non-linear behavior of phase-equilibrium calculation methods
 tends to amplify what would otherwise be acceptably small errors.
 It is therefore recommended that PRSV2 be used for equilibrium calculations
 when applying these models to a design.
 However, once the equilibrium state has been determined, the phase specific
 thermodynamic values at equilibrium may be determined by one of several
 simpler models with a reasonable degree of accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chao-Seader and Grayson-Streed models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chao-Seader (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chao1961"

\end_inset

) and Grayson-Streed (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Grayson1963"

\end_inset

) are older, semi-empirical models.
 The Grayson-Streed correlation is an extension of the Chao-Seader method
 with special applicability to hydrogen.
 In DWSIM, only the equilibrium values produced by these correlations are
 used in the calculations.
 The Lee-Kesler method is used to determine the enthalpy and entropy of
 liquid and vapor phases.
\end_layout

