\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a factor used in thermodynamics to account for deviations from ideal
 behaviour in a mixture of chemical substances.
 In an ideal mixture, the interactions between each pair of chemical species
 are the same (or more formally, the enthalpy of mixing is zero) and, as
 a result, properties of the mixtures can be expressed directly in terms
 of simple concentrations or partial pressures of the substances present.
 Deviations from ideality are accommodated by modifying the concentration
 by an activity coefficient.
 .
 The activity coefficient is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{i}=[\frac{\partial(nG^{E}/RT)}{\partial n{}_{i}}]_{P,T,n_{j\neq i}}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{E}$
\end_inset

 represents the excess Gibbs energy of the liquid solution, which is a measure
 of how far the solution is from ideal behavior.
 For an ideal solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 = 1.
 Expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{E}/RT$
\end_inset

 provide values for the activity coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
UNIQUAC and UNIFAC models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UNIQUAC equation considers 
\begin_inset Formula $g\equiv G^{E}/RT$
\end_inset

 formed by two additive parts, one combinatorial term 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{C}$
\end_inset

 to take into account the size of the molecules, and one residual term 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{R}$
\end_inset

, which take into account the interactions between molecules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g\equiv g^{C}+g^{R}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{C}$
\end_inset

 function contains only pure species parameters, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{R}$
\end_inset

 function incorporates two binary parameters for each pair of molecules.
 For a multicomponent system, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{C}=\sum_{i}x_{i}\ln\phi_{i}/x_{i}+5\sum_{i}q_{i}x_{i}\ln\theta_{i}/\phi_{i}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{R}=-\sum_{i}q_{i}x_{i}\ln(\sum_{j}\theta_{j}\tau_{j}i)\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{i}\equiv(x_{i}r_{i})/(\sum_{j}x_{j}r_{j})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\theta_{i}\equiv(x_{i}q_{i})/(\sum_{j}x_{j}q_{j})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 subscript indicates the species, and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an index that represents all the species, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 included.
 All sums are over all the species.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ij}\neq\tau_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ii}=\tau_{jj}=1$
\end_inset

.
 In these equations, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 (a relative molecular volume) and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 (a relative molecular surface area) are pure species parameters.
 The influence of temperature in 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 enters by means of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ij}$
\end_inset

 parameters, which are temperature-dependent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau_{ij}=\exp(u_{ij}-u_{jj})/RT\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This way, the UNIQUAC parameters are values of 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{ij}-u_{jj})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is found through the application of the following relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}=\left[\partial(nG^{E}/RT)/\partial n_{i}\right]{}_{(P,T,n_{j\neq i})}\label{eq:gamaiuniquac}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is represented by the following equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}=\ln\gamma_{i}^{C}+\ln\gamma_{i}^{R}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}^{C}=1-J_{i}+\ln J_{i}-5q_{i}(1-J_{i}/L_{i}+\ln J_{i}/L_{i})\label{eq:gic}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}^{R}=q_{i}(1-\ln s_{i}-\sum_{j}\theta_{j}\tau_{ij}/s_{j})\label{eq:ric}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
J_{i}=r_{i}/(\sum_{j}r_{j}x_{j})\label{eq:ji}\\
L=q_{i}/(\sum_{j}q_{j}x_{j})\label{eq:li}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{i}=\sum_{l}\theta_{l}\tau_{li}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 subscript identify the species, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 are indexes which represent all the species, including 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 all sums are over all the species, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

.
 The parameters values 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{ij}-u_{jj})$
\end_inset

 are found by regression of binary VLE/LLE data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UNIFAC method for the estimation of activity coefficients depends on
 the concept of that a liquid mixture can be considered a solution of its
 own molecules.
 These structural units are called subgroups.
 The greatest advantage of this method is that a relatively small number
 of subgroups can be combined to form a very large number of molecules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The activity coefficients do not only depend on the subgroup properties,
 but also on the interactions between these groups.
 Similar subgroups are related to a main group, like “CH2”, “OH”, “ACH”
 etc.; the identification of the main groups are only descriptive.
 All the subgroups that belongs to the same main group are considered identical
 with respect to the interaction between groups.
 Consequently, the parameters which characterize the interactions between
 the groups are identified by pairs of the main groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UNIFAC method is based on the UNIQUAC equation, where the activity coefficie
nts are given by the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamaiuniquac"

\end_inset

.
 When applied to a solution of groups, the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gic"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ric"

\end_inset

 are written in the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}^{C}=1-J_{i}+\ln J_{i}-5q_{i}(1-J_{i}/L_{i}+\ln J_{i}/L_{i})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}^{R}=q_{i}(1-\sum_{k}(\theta_{k}\beta_{ik}/s_{k})-e_{ki}ln\beta_{ik}/s_{k})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{i}$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}$
\end_inset

 are still given by eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ji2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:li2"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the following definitions apply: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{i}=\sum_{k}\nu_{k}^{(i)}R_{k}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q_{i}=\sum_{k}\nu_{k}^{(i)}Q_{k}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
e_{ki}=(\nu_{k}^{(i)}Q_{k})/q_{i}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\beta_{ik}=\sum_{m}e_{mk}\tau_{mk}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\theta_{k}=(\sum_{i}x_{i}q_{i}e_{ki})/(\sum_{i}x_{j}q_{j})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{k}=\sum_{m}\theta_{m}\tau_{mk}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{i}=\sum_{l}\theta_{l}\tau_{li}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau_{mk}=\exp(-a_{mk})/T\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 subscript identify the species, and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an index that goes through all the species.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 subscript identify the subgroups, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is an index that goes through all the subgroups.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{k}^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 is the number of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 subgroup in a molecule of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 species.
 The subgroup parameter values 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 and the interaction parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $-a_{mk}$
\end_inset

 are obtained in the literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\series bold
\emph on
Modified UNIFAC (Dortmund) model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UNIFAC model, despite being widely used in various applications, has
 some limitations which are, in some way, inherent to the model.
 Some of these limitations are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
UNIFAC is unable to distinguish between some types of isomers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma-\phi$
\end_inset

 approach limits the use of UNIFAC for applications under the pressure range
 of 10-15 atm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The temperature is limited within the range of approximately 275-425 K.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Non-condensable gases and supercritical components are not included.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Proximity effects are not taken into account.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The parameters of liquid-liquid equilibrium are different from those of
 vapor-liquid equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Polymers are not included.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Electrolytes are not included.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of these limitations can be overcome.
 The insensitivity of some types of isomers can be eliminated through a
 careful choice of the groups used to represent the molecules.
 The fact that the parameters for the liquid-liquid equilibrium are different
 from those for the vapor-liquid equilibrium seems not to have a theoretical
 solution at this time.
 One solution is to use both data from both equiibria to determine the parameter
s as a modified UNIFAC model.
 The limitations on the pressure and temperature can be overcome if the
 UNIFAC model is used with equations of state, which carry with them the
 dependencies of pressure and temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These limitations of the original UNIFAC model have led several authors
 to propose changes in both combinatorial and the residual parts.
 To modify the combinatorial part, the basis is the suggestion given by
 Kikic et al.
 (1980) in the sense that the Staverman-Guggenheim correction on the original
 term of Flory-Huggins is very small and can, in most cases, be neglected.
 As a result, this correction was empirically removed from the UNIFAC model.
 Among these modifications, the proposed by Gmehling and coworkers [Weidlich
 and Gmehling, 1986; Weidlich and Gmehling, 1987; Gmehling et al., 1993],
 known as the model UNIFAC-Dortmund, is one of the most promising.
 In this model, the combinatorial part of the original UNIFAC is replaced
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}^{C}=1-J_{i}+\ln J_{i}-5q_{i}(1-J_{i}/L_{i}+\ln J_{i}/L_{i})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
J_{i}=r_{i}^{3/4}/(\sum_{j}r_{j}^{3/4}x_{j})\label{eq:ji2}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the remaining quantities is defined the same way as in the original
 UNIFAC.
 Thus, the correction in-Staverman Guggenheim is empirically taken from
 the template.
 It is important to note that the in the UNIFAC-Dortmund model, the quantities
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 are no longer calculated on the volume and surface area of Van der Waals
 forces, as proposed by Bondi (1968), but are additional adjustable parameters
 of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The residual part is still given by the solution for groups, just as in
 the original UNIFAC, but now the parameters of group interaction are considered
 temperature dependent, according to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau_{mk}=\exp(-a_{mk}^{(0)}+a_{mk}^{(1)}T+a_{mk}^{(2)}T^{2})/T\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These parameters must be estimated from experimental phase equilibrium data.
 Gmehling et al.
 (1993) presented an array of parameters for 45 major groups, adjusted using
 data from the vapor-liquid equilibrium, excess enthalpies, activity coefficient
s at infinite dilution and liquid-liquid equilibrium.
 enthalpy and entropy of liquid and vapor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Modified UNIFAC (NIST) model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kang2015128"

\end_inset

 is similar to the Modified UNIFAC (Dortmund), with new modified UNIFAC
 parameters reported for 89 main groups and 984 group–group interactions
 using critically evaluated phase equilibrium data including vapor–liquid
 equilibrium (VLE), liquid–liquid equilibrium (LLE), solid–liquid equilibrium
 (SLE), excess enthalpy (HE), infinite dilution activity coefficient (AINF)
 and excess heat capacity (CPE) data.
 A new algorithmic framework for quality assessment of phase equilibrium
 data was applied for qualifying the consistency of data and screening out
 possible erroneous data.
 Substantial improvement over previous versions of UNIFAC is observed due
 to inclusion of experimental data from recent publications and proper weighting
 based on a quality assessment procedure.
 The systems requiring further verification of phase equilibrium data were
 identified where insufficient number of experimental data points is available
 or where existing data are conflicting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
NRTL model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wilson (1964) presented a model relating 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{E}$
\end_inset

 to the molar fraction, based mainly on molecular considerations, using
 the concept of local composition.
 Basically, the concept of local composition states that the composition
 of the system in the vicinity of a given molecule is not equal to the overall
 composition of the system, because of intermolecular forces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wilson's equation provides a good representation of the Gibbs' excess free
 energy for a variety of mixtures, and is particularly useful in solutions
 of polar compounds or with a tendency to association in apolar solvents,
 where Van Laar's equation or Margules' one are not sufficient.
 Wilson's equation has the advantage of being easily extended to multicomponent
 solutions but has two disadvantages: first, the less important, is that
 the equations are not applicable to systems where the logarithms of activity
 coefficients, when plotted as a function of 
\emph on
x
\emph default
, show a maximum or a minimum.
 However, these systems are not common.
 The second, a little more serious, is that the model of Wilson is not able
 to predict limited miscibility, that is, it is not useful for LLE calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Renon and Prausnitz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Renon1968"

\end_inset

 developed the 
\emph on
NRTL
\emph default
 equation 
\emph on
(Non-Random, Two-Liquid)
\emph default
 based on the concept of local composition but, unlike Wilson's model, the
 NRTL model is applicable to systems of partial miscibility.
 The model equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ln\gamma_{i}=\frac{\underset{j=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}\tau_{ji}x_{j}G_{ji}}{\underset{k=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}x_{k}G_{ki}}+\underset{j=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}\frac{x_{j}G_{ij}}{\underset{k=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}x_{k}G_{kj}}\left(\tau_{ij}-\frac{\underset{m=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}\tau_{mj}x_{m}G_{mj}}{\underset{k=1}{\overset{n}{\sum}}x_{k}G_{kj}}\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{ij}=exp(-\tau_{ij}\alpha_{ij}),\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau_{ij}=a_{ij}/RT,\end{equation}

\end_inset


