\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Liquid Phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Liquid phase density is calculated with the Rackett equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reid1987"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{s}=\frac{RT_{C}}{P_{C}}Z_{RA}^{\left[1+\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{2/7}\right]},\label{eq:liqdens}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $V_{s}$
\end_inset

 Saturated molar volume (m³/mol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 Critical temperature (K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}$
\end_inset

 Critical pressure (Pa)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{r}$
\end_inset

 Reduced temperature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{RA}$
\end_inset

 Rackett constant of the component (or the mixture)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 Ideal Gas constant (8,314 J/[mol.K])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
\noindent
\align left

\family sans
\size scriptsize
\emph on
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T\geqslant T_{cm},$
\end_inset

 the Rackett method does not provide a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{s}$
\end_inset

 and, in this case, DWSIM uses the EOS-generated compressibility factor
 to calculate the density of the liquid phase.
\end_layout

\end_inset

For mixtures, the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liqdens"

\end_inset

 becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{s}=R\left(\sum\frac{x_{i}T_{c_{i}}}{P_{c_{i}}}\right)Z_{RA}^{\left[1+\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{2/7}\right]},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T_{r}=T/T_{cm}$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{c_{m}}=\sum\sum\phi_{i}\phi_{j}T_{c_{ij}},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi_{i}=\frac{x_{i}V_{c_{i}}}{\sum x_{i}V_{c_{i}}},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{c_{ij}}=\left[\frac{8\left(V_{c_{i}}V_{c_{j}}\right)^{1/2}}{\left(V_{c_{i}}^{1/3}+V_{c_{j}}^{1/3}\right)^{3}}\right]\left(T_{c_{i}}T_{c_{j}}\right)^{1/2},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 Molar fraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $V_{c_{i}}$
\end_inset

 Critical volume (m³/mol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{RA}$
\end_inset

 isn't available, it is calculated from the component acentric factor,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Z_{RA}=0.2956-0.08775\omega,\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the component (or mixture) isn't saturated, a correction is applied in
 order to account for the effect of pressure in the volume,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V=V_{s}\left[1-\left(0.0861488+0.0344483\omega\right)\ln\frac{\beta+P}{\beta+P_{vp}}\right],\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\beta}{P} & = & -1-9.070217\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{1/3}+62.45326\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{2/3}-135.1102\left(1-T_{r}\right)+\nonumber \\
 &  & +\exp\left(4.79594+0.250047\omega+1.14188\omega^{2}\right)\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{4/3},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 Compressed liquid volume (m³/mol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 Pressure (Pa)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $P_{vp}$
\end_inset

 Vapor pressure / Bubble point pressure (Pa)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, density is calculated from the molar volume by the following relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho=\frac{MM}{1000V},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 Density (kg/m³)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 Specific volume of the fluid (m³/mol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $MM$
\end_inset

 Liquid phase molecular volume (kg/kmol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Vapor Phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
\noindent
\align left

\family sans
\size scriptsize
\emph on
For the 
\emph default
Ideal Gas
\emph on
 Property Package, the compressibility factor is considered to be equal
 to 1.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Vapor phase density is calculated from the compressiblity factor generated
 by the EOS, according with the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho=\frac{MM\, P}{1000ZRT},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 Density (kg/m³)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $MM$
\end_inset

 Molecular weight of the vapor phase (kg/kmol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 Pressure (Pa)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 Vapor phase compressibility factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 Ideal Gas constant (8,314 J/[mol.K])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 Temperature (K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Mixture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there are two phases at system temperature and pressure, the density
 of the mixture is calculated by the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{m}=f_{l}\rho_{l}+f_{v}\rho_{v},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{m,l,v}$
\end_inset

 Density of the mixture / liquid phase / vapor phase (kg/m³)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $f_{l,v}$
\end_inset

 Volumetric fraction of the liquid phase / vapor phase (kg/kmol)
