\begin_layout Subsection
Viscosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Liquid Phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When experimental data is not available, liquid phase viscosity is calculated
 from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\eta_{L}=\exp\left(\sum_{i}x_{i}\ln\eta_{i}\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the viscosity of each component in the phase, which depends on the temperatu
re and is calculated from experimental data.
 Dependence of viscosity with the temperature is described in the equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\eta=\exp\left(A+B/T+C\ln T+DT^{E}\right),\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\emph on
A, B, C, D 
\emph default
and
\emph on
 E
\emph default
 are experimental coefficients (or generated by DWSIM in the case of pseudocompo
nents or hypotheticals).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Vapor Phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vapor phase viscosity is calculated in two steps.
 First, when experimental data is not available, the temperature dependence
 is given by the 
\emph on
Lucas
\emph default
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reid1987"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\eta\xi=\left[0,.807T_{r}^{0,618}-0.357\exp(-0.449T_{r})+0.34\exp(-4.058T_{r})+0.018\right]\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\xi=0,176\left(\frac{T_{c}}{MM^{3}P_{c}^{4}}\right)^{1/6},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 Viscosity (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu P$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c},P_{c}$
\end_inset

 Component (or mixture) critical properties 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{r}$
\end_inset

 Reduced temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $T/T_{c}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $MM$
\end_inset

 Molecular weight (kg/kmol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second step, the experimental or calculated viscosity with the Lucas
 method is corrected to take into account the effect of pressure, by the
 
\emph on
Jossi-Stiel-Thodos
\emph default
 method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reid1987"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left[\left(\eta-\eta_{0}\right)\left(\frac{T_{c}}{MM^{3}P_{c}^{4}}\right)^{1/6}+1\right]^{1/4} & = & 1.023+0.23364\rho_{r}+\nonumber \\
 & + & 0.58533\rho_{r}^{2}-0.40758\rho_{r}^{3}+0.093324\rho_{r}^{4},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\eta,\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

 Corrected viscosity / Lucas method calculated viscosity (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu P$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c},P_{c}$
\end_inset

 Component critical properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{r}$
\end_inset

 Reduced density, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho/\rho_{c}=V/V_{c}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $MM$
\end_inset

 Molecular weight (kg/kmol)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the vapor phase contains more than a component, the viscosity is calculated
 by the same procedure, but with the required properties calculated by a
 molar average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Surface Tension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When experimental data is not available, the liquid phase surface tension
 is calculated by doing a molar average of the individual component tensions,
 which are calculated with the 
\emph on
Brock
\emph default
-
\emph on
Bird
\emph default
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reid1987"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\sigma}{P_{c}^{2/3}T_{c}^{1/3}}=\left(0.132\alpha_{c}-0.279\right)\left(1-T_{r}\right)^{11/9}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{c}=0.9076\left[1+\frac{T_{br}\ln(P_{c}/1.01325)}{1-T_{br}}\right],\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 Surface tension (N/m)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 Critical temperature (K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}$
\end_inset

 Critical pressure (Pa)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $T_{br}$
\end_inset

 Reduced normal boiling point, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{b}/T_{c}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

