\begin_layout Standard
The models for natural gas hydrates equilibrium calculations are mostly
 based in statistical thermodynamics to predict in which temperature and
 pressure conditions there will be formation or dissociation of hydrates.
 In these conditions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f_{w}^{i}=f_{w}^{H},\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that is, the fugacity of water in hydrate is the same as in the water in
 any other phase present at equilibria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference in the models present in DWSIM is mainly in the way that
 water fugacity in the hydrate phase is calculated.
 In the modified van der Waals and Platteeuw model, the isofugacity criteria
 is used indirectly through chemical potentials, which must also be equal
 in the equilibria:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu_{w}^{i}=\mu_{w}^{H}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
remembering that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f_{i}=x_{i}P\exp((\mu_{i}-\mu_{i}^{gi})/RT).\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Modified van der Waals and Platteeuw (Parrish and Prausnitz) method 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classic model for determination of equilibrium pressures and temperatures
 was developed by van der Waals and Platteeuw.
 This model was later extended by Parrish and Prausnitz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ParrishW.R._i260041a006"

\end_inset

 to take into account multiple "guests" in the hydrate structures.
 The condition of equilibrium used in the 
\emph on
vdwP
\emph default
 model is the equality of the chemical potential of water in the hydrate
 phase and in the other phases, which can be liquid, solid or both.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*

\emph on
Chemical potential of water in the hydrate phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the modified var der Waals method, the chemical potential of water in
 the hydrate phase is calculated by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu_{w}^{H}=\mu_{w}^{\beta}+RT\sum_{m}\nu_{m}\ln(1-\sum_{j}\theta_{mj}),\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{w}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the chemical potential of water in the empty hydrate lattice (something
 like an "ideal" chemical potential) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the number of 
\emph on
m
\emph default
 cavities by water molecule in the lattice.
 The fraction of cavities 
\emph on
m-type
\emph default
 cavities occupied by the gaseous component 
\emph on
l
\emph default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\theta_{ml}=(C_{ml}f_{i})/((1+\sum_{j}C_{mj}f_{j})),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{mj}$
\end_inset

 is the Langmuir constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $fi$
\end_inset

 is the fugacity of the gaseous component 
\emph on
l
\emph default
.
 The Langmuir constant takes into account the interactions between the gas
 and the molecules of water in the cavities.
 Using the Lennard-Jones-Devonshire cell theory, van der Waals e Platteeuw
 showed that the Langmuir constant can be given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
C(T)=4\pi/kT\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp[(-w(r))/kT]r^{2}dr,\end{equation}

\end_inset

where T is the absolute temperature, k is the Boltzmann constant and 
\emph on
w(r)
\emph default
 is the spherically symmetric potential which is a function of the cell
 radius, the coordination number and the nature of the gas-water interaction.
 In this method, the Kihara potential with a spherical core is used,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w(r)=2ze[\sigma^{12}/(R^{11}r)(\delta^{10}+a/R\delta^{11})-\sigma^{6}/(R^{5}r)(\delta^{4}+a/R\delta^{5})],\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta^{N}=[(1-r/R-a/R)^{-N})-(1+r/R-a/R)^{-N})]/N,\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\emph on
